{
  "ADUs": {
    "ADU1": {
      "text": "We argue that artificial systems such as robots currently lack the genuine embodied embeddedness that allows the type of self-organization that is relevant to consciousness.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU2": {
      "text": "In this tradition, the human mind has an inner characteristic and conscious human beings, living in a particular and personal world, are the only ones to access, directly through private introspection, their own mental states.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU3": {
      "text": "Consciousness, especially in its self-reflexive mode, was considered to be a unique prerogative of humans.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU4": {
      "text": "In Ryle's view, the mind is characterized in terms of '…abilities, liabilities, and inclination to do and undergo certain sorts of things, and of the doing and undergoing of these things in the ordinary [external] world' (199, p. 190).",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU5": {
      "text": "From this perspective, consciousness is not a unique prerogative of humans, but it is spread all around, throughout the evolution of life.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU6": {
      "text": "Fundamental to this approach is the contrast between animate and inanimate properties of open systems.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU7": {
      "text": "The problem with the mechanistic (robot-like) view is that it does not take into consideration the notion of autonomy, which he considers a fundamental characteristic of intelligent behaviour.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU8": {
      "text": "Autonomous activity, as Bertalanffy stresses it, 'is the most primitive form of behaviour (…) it is found in brain function (Hebb, 1949) and in psychological processes (…) All such behaviour is performed for its own sake, deriving gratification (…) from the performance itself' (p.209).",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU9": {
      "text": "In this sense, it is difficult to see how they could incorporate any degree of autonomy in their behaviour.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU10": {
      "text": "By using the metaphor of a dance, we want to stress that the temporal aspects of the active (not merely reactive) interaction between body and environment are of considerable importance to the emergence of consciousness.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU11": {
      "text": "One hypothesis to be further explained is that an important function of this type of basic consciousness is the maintenance of the main parameters of the organisms in order to enhance its autonomy and to preserve life.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU12": {
      "text": "Finally, we shall argue that consciousness, understood in this basic, action-related sense, is not an exclusive property of humans, but it is a common element of all organisms.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU13": {
      "text": "Consciousness is not a pre-condition for action and thought, but rather an emergent product of self-organized action, which integrates sensory experiences, volition, emotion and memory, producing a unified informational field.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU14": {
      "text": "The complex system theory (CST) presupposes the existence of an order in the empirical, macroscopic, world, experienced in every day life, that can be described by information of a more general category (of a second order).",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU15": {
      "text": "Such a unifying order cannot be reduced to the summation of its constitutive parts, but involves global, new, characteristics emergent from the interaction between individual parts of complex systems.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU16": {
      "text": "Emergent properties can be observed in a wide variety of self-organizing systems.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU17": {
      "text": "Self-organization may lead to the development of dispositions.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU18": {
      "text": "Dispositions can be understood as the inclination of a system to produce specific behaviour upon encountering adequate conditions.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU19": {
      "text": "Actions incorporate an intricate web of dispositions that are susceptible of corrections and adjustments.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU20": {
      "text": "It seems to be the spontaneous ability to 'dance' with the flow of internal and external tensions that is constitutive of the action-related type of consciousness, which distinguishes intelligent from merely mechanic behaviour.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU21": {
      "text": "The brain does not give orders to be executed but provides a contribution to the ongoing dance between the body, brain and environment.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU22": {
      "text": "In our view, so far robots lack a genuine embodied embeddedness, precluding the emergence of action-based consciousness.",
      "label": "claim"
    }
  },
